Data Visualization using Matplotlib 

Lab Exercises
Exercise 1:
Plot a histogram for the CRIM (crime rate) variable and describe its distribution.
Code:

# ! pip install numpy
! pip install pandas
! pip install matplotlib
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

data=pd.read_csv('boston.csv')
plt.hist(data['CRIM'], bins=30, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')
plt.title("Distribution of crime rates(CRIM)")
plt.xlabel("crime rate")
plt.ylabel("frequency")
plt.show()
 
Exercise 2:
Create a scatter plot showing the relationship between DIS (distance to employment centers) and MEDV.
Code:

# ! pip install numpy
! pip install pandas
! pip install matplotlib
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

data=pd.read_csv('boston.csv')
plt.scatter(data['DIS'],data['MEDV'], color='teal')
plt.title("Relationship between DIS and MEDV")
plt.xlabel("average number of rooms per dwell ing (DIS)")
plt.ylabel("price of homes(MEDV)")
plt.show()
 
Exercise 3:
Plot a bar chart showing the average MEDV for different RAD (accessibility to highways) values.
Code:

# ! pip install numpy
! pip install pandas
! pip install matplotlib
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

avg_price = data.groupby('RAD')['MEDV'].mean()
plt.bar(avg_price.index, avg_price.values, color='green')
plt.title("Average MEDV by RAD")
plt.ylabel("Average House Price ($1000s)")
plt.show()

Exercise 4:
Draw a boxplot for MEDV across different RAD categories.
Code:

# ! pip install numpy
! pip install pandas
! pip install matplotlib
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data.boxplot(column='MEDV',by='RAD',grid=False)
plt.title("boxplot of MEDV by RAD")
plt.suptitle('')
plt.xlabel("RAD (0=no,1=yes)")
plt.ylabel("house price ($1000s)")
plt.show()
